==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harry
<hw>Har"ry</hw> <pr>(-r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Harried</conjf> <pr>(-r⟦icr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Harrying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>harwen</ets>, <ets>herien</ets>, <ets>her⟦yogh⟧ien</ets>, AS.
<ets>hergian</ets> to act as an army, to ravage, plunder, fr.
<ets>here</ets> army; akin to G. <ets>heer</ets>, Icel. <ets>herr</ets>,
Goth. <ets>harjis</ets>, and Lith. <ets>karas</ets> war. Cf.
<er>Harbor</er>, <er>Herald</er>, <er>Heriot</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To strip; to pillage; to lay waste; <as>as, the
Northmen came several times and <ex>harried</ex> the
land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>harry</qex> this beautiful region.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A red squirrel had <qex>harried</qex> the nest of a wood
thrush.</q> <rj><qau>J. Burroughs.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To agitate; to worry; to harrow; to harass.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To ravage; plunder; pillage; lay waste; vex;
tease; worry; annoy; harass.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Harry
<hw>Har"ry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a predatory incursion; to
plunder or lay waste.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Beau. &
Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harry</ent>⟦br⟧

